"Jacobson M.Z.","Climate response of fossil fuel and biofuel soot, accounting for soot's feedback to snow and sea ice albedo and emissivity",2004,"Journal of Geophysical Research D: Atmospheres","109","21",,"D21201 1","15",,,10.1029/2004JD004945,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-13244270269&partnerID=40&md5=39b3a92968ef93cba66ae8aa8bce1a2d","Department of Civil/Environ. Eng., Stanford University, Terman Engineering Center, Stanford, CA 94305-4020, United States","Jacobson, M.Z., Department of Civil/Environ. Eng., Stanford University, Terman Engineering Center, Stanford, CA 94305-4020, United States","The first three-dimensional global model in which time-dependent spectral albedos and emissivities over snow and sea ice are predicted with a radiative transfer solution, rather than prescribed, is applied to study the climate response of fossil fuel plus biofuel black carbon plus organic matter (ff+bf BC+OM) when BC absorption in snow and sea ice is accounted for. The model treats the cycling of size-resolved BC+OM between emission and removal by dry deposition and precipitation from first principles. Particles produce and enter size-resolved clouds and precipitation by nucleation scavenging and aerosol-hydrometeor coagulation. Removal brings BC to the surface, where internally and externally mixed BC in snow and sea ice affects albedo and emissivity through radiative transfer. Climate response simulations were run with a ff+bf BC+OC emission inventory lower than that used in a previous study. The 10-year, globally averaged ff+bf BC+OM near-surface temperature respouse due to all feedbacks was about +0.27 K (+0.32 in the last 3 years), close to those from the previous study (5-year average of +0. 3 K and fifth-year warming of +0.35 K) and its modeled range (+0.15 to +0.5 K) because warming due to soot absorption in snow and sea ice here (10-year average of +0.06 K with a modeled range of +0.03 to +0.11 K) offset reduced warming due to lower emission. BC was calculated to reduce snow and sea ice albedo by ∼0.4% in the global average and 1% in the Northern Hemisphere. The globally averaged modeled BC concentration in snow and sea ice was ∼5 ng/g; that in rainfall was ∼22 ng/g. About 98% of BC removal from the atmosphere was due to precipitation; the rest was due to dry deposition. The results here support previous findings that controlling ff+bf BC+OM and CO 2 emission may slow global warming. Copyright 2004 by the American Geophysical Union.","Albedo; Black carbon; Climate change; Feedbacks; Radiative effects; Snow","albedo; anthropogenic effect; black carbon; climate change; climate forcing; fossil fuel; radiative forcing",,,,,,"Ackerman, T.P., Toon, O.B., Absorption of visible radiation in atmosphere containing mixtures of absorbing and nonabsorbing particles (1981) Appl. Opt., 20, pp. 3661-3667; Aoki, T., Aoki, T., Fukabori, M., Hachikubo, A., Tachibana, Y., Nishio, F., Effects of snow physical parameters on spectral albedo and bi-directional reflectance of snow surface (2000) J. Geophys. Res., 105, pp. 10,219-10,236; Arakawa, A., Lamb, V.R., A potential enstrophy and energy conserving scheme for the shallow water equations (1981) Mon. Weather Rev., 109, pp. 18-36; Bohren, C.F., Applicability of effective-medium theories to problems of scattering and absorption by nonhomogeneous atmospheric particles (1986) J. Atmos. Sci., 43, pp. 468-475; Bond, T.C., Streets, D.G., Yarber, K.F., Nelson, S.M., Woo, J., Klimont, Z., A technology-based global inventory of black and organic carbon emissions from combustion (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109, pp. D14203. , doi:10.1029/2003JD003697; Chylek, P., Ramaswamy, V., Srivastava, V., Albedo of soot-contaminated snow (1983) J. Geophys. Res., 88, pp. 10,837-10,843; Chylek, P., Srivastava, V., Cahenzli, L., Pinnick, R.G., Dod, R.L., Novakov, T., Cook, T.L., Hinds, B.D., Aerosol and graphitic carbon content of snow (1987) J. Geophys. Res., 92, pp. 9801-9809; Chylek, P., Srivastava, V